	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		I couldn't sleep a wink.  Scrap and I were up late theorizing about the connection between gamersbeatches.net and Treesoft.Was this just a coincidence that Sven's P2P application shared information that was sensitive to Treesoft?  Was it a coincidence that someone at GB just happened to do a keyword search for items that turned up on Sven's drive?  If there was an insider at Treesoft trying to do the company in, why not just email the documents home or steal them on a thumb drive?  Why go through all this hassle?<br/><br/>Scrap had fallen asleep on the floor of my hotel room and, as usual, was snoring louder than Delta Burke on a lazy Sunday afternoon.  <br/><br/>I closed my eyes and struggled to get a few hours sleep.  The facts of the case were whipping around in my brain so fast that my eyes were rotating in their sockets.  Had I missed a clue?  Had I overlooked an obvious fact?  Was I making ridiculous assumptions? <br/><br/>"Screw this." I said as I rolled off of my bed and nearly stepped on the Scraptop, perched carelessly on the floor.  A quick glance at the clock revealed the time to be 0600 hours.<br/><br/>It was coffee time.<br/><br/>I grabbed my notepad and Powerbook and jumped in the elevator.  I was a short walking distance from the temple of the brewed brown bean.  <br/><br/>My eyes started to rotate again.  The thoughts returned.  <br/><br/>I had missed something. <br/><br/>Minutes later I was rushing back up the elevator, laptop bag slung over my shoulder and two venti coffees in my hands.<br/><br/>"Scrap!  Scrap!  Wake up and clean up.  We need to drive over to Treesoft first thing." I said as I handed Scrap his coffee.<br/><br/>Scrap rubbed his eyes. "Dude, I had the weirdest dream.  I dreamt that Barbie from our <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150/http://networking.ittoolbox.com/blogs/featuredentry.asp?i=4710">Minotaur case</a> was washing my car and eating a hamburger at the same time..."  <br/><br/>I really should work alone.<br/><br/>Several hours later we finally arrived at Treesoft HQ.  I unlocked our office door and threw one of the banker's boxes of records at Scrap.<br/><br/>"What gives?" Scrap complained.  "Did you switch to espresso or something?  Calm down!"<br/><br/>His comments were a whisper.  I had zeroed in on the bankers box that I wanted and was feverishly going through all of the current employee records again, one by one.<br/><br/>"You want me to go interview Sven when he gets in?  You look a little psycho." Scrap said.<br/><br/>"What?" I snapped back.<br/><br/>"Preoccupied!  You look preoccupied." Scrap responded, correcting himself accordingly.<br/><br/>"Fine." I said as I waved him back out the door.  I had found what I was looking for.<br/><br/>Scrap entered Sven's office to a familiar sight.  Sven was staring deep into his monitor, trance music beating into his ears via headphones.<br/><br/>"Yo." Scrap said as he waved his monkey paws in front of Sven's face.<br/><br/>Sven jumped.  Again.<br/><br/>"Scrap!  Scrap!  Hey, I'm glad you're here.  Check out this wicked piece of japanese anime I snagged from some dude!" Sven said as restored a minimized media player window.<br/><br/>"Sven, what gives with the Limewire window? I talked to Kurt last night and he said that P2P software is banned here." Scrap asked in a most sincere voice.<br/><br/>"Aw, Kurt is so anally-retentive about this network.  I bet he burps up pearls. I just turn it on for searches.  Okay, here's the video!" Sven said as he maximized the video window.<br/><br/>"Seriously man, can I ask you what directories you have shared on your machine?" Scrap queried.<br/><br/>Sven looked confused.<br/><br/>"Uh, my 'stuff' directory.  That's all I ever share out.  Check it out, I have movies, music, some cool pictures of sheep ..."<br/><br/>Scrap ran around third base and aimed for home.  "Sven, can you bring up your preferences in Limewire?" <br/><br/>Without a flinch, Sven clicked through menu options.<br/><br/>"Ya, and?" Sven asked.<br/><br/>Scrap reached towards the sky with his monkey paw and scratched his head.<br/><br/>The only directory shared was C:\STUFF.<br/><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150/http://www.esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=98078-060309-897911-68"><img alt="esbn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/esbnicon.asp?id=9807806030989791168" border="0"> 98078-060309-897911-68</a> Rate content: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=9807806030989791168&amp;rate=yes"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbup.gif" border="0"></a><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=9807806030989791168&amp;rate=no"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbdown.gif" border="0"></a><br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/barcode.asp?code=9807806030989791168&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"></p><p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
<tr><td><img style="margin-right: 9px; float: left" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150im_/http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/s_610000.jpg"><b><font face="Arial" size="4">DID YOU KNOW?</b></font><font face="Arial" size="2"><p style="margin-top: 2px">You can read all of SecurityMonkey's case files! <br>Find them <b><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/official-securitymonkey-case-file-index-14787">here</a></b>. <br><br>You can also read all of SecurityMonkey's <br>'Banana Cupboard' stories <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707132150/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/banana-cupboard-stories-index-25647">here</a>.  <br><br>You may not get a lot done for a few hours... or even days.</font><br><br>The reviews are in...<br><br><i>"Completely addictive... suspenseful and informative at the same time!"<br>"A mix of classic detective scripting, timing, and technology..."<br>"Cleverly injected humor makes these case files easy to read and hard to put down!"</i></td></tr></table><hr><p>
